{"cursor":"6070","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox Television\n| show_name = The Assistant image = caption = show_name_2 = genre = Reality\n| Comedy format = creator = developer = writer = director = Kasey\n| Barrett Jeff Fisher creative_director = presenter = Andy Dick starring =\n| judges = voices = narrated = theme_music_composer = opentheme = endtheme =\n| composer = country = language = English num_seasons = 1 num_episodes = 8\n| list_episodes = executive_producer = producer = editor = location =\n| cinematography = camera = runtime = 25 minutes company = distributor = channel\n| = MTV picture_format = audio_format = first_run = first_aired = 12 July 2004\n| last_aired = 30 August 2004 status = Ended preceded_by = followed_by = related\n| = website = http://mtv.com/onair/dyn/the_assistant/series.jhtml\n| production_website =\n}}\n\n'The Assistant' is a reality television show that parodied other reality shows\nsuch as [[The Apprentice (U.S. TV series)|The Apprentice]], [[The Bachelor (US\nTV series)|The Bachelor]], [[The Bachelorette]], [[Survivor (TV\nseries)|Survivor]], [[American Idol]], and [[Fear Factor]]. Its eight episodes\noriginally aired on MTV. It featured comedian Andy Dick's search for a new\npersonal assistant. The beginning of the first episode parodied The Bachelor,\nwith the twelve contestants arriving in limousines, and Dick waiting outside to\ngreet them with his maid and butler. A \"rose ceremony\" immediately followed, and\none contestant was eliminated.\n\nDick assigned the Hollywood hopefuls to some absurd tasks such as pretending to\nbe him in an interview with a Japanese television station, bringing him coffee\nby traversing on a beam over a swimming pool, breaking up with his girlfriend,\nand attempting to get him a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame.\n\nContestants were usually \"snipped\" in elimination ceremonies parodying those on\nother reality series. Like some other programs, The Assistant also\nincluded double elimination episodes and brought back fired candidates. Driving\nhome Dick's message that they were starting from the bottom, candidates slept in\nDick's garage. He also woke them with a flashing, siren-generating alarm, was\nprone to tantrums, and griped that, \"This reality show is ruining my\nlife!\"\n\nAndy Dick actually had a relationship with one of the contestants on the show.\nAndy and Sarah Beckworth dated for a while after the show's end. The end of the\nrelationship led to a breach of contract lawsuit with MTV which prohibited\nrelationships with the contestants.\n\nThough the show was satire, the twelve contestants were real and the winner,\nMelissa Ordway, was awarded several prizes including a job at MTV.\nThe runner-up was Mark, who had been fired, but was brought back in the seventh\nepisode. The show was not renewed after its first season.\n","linknr":135,"url":"The_Assistant_(television)","recorded":1374523042,"links":["/w/index.php?title=The_Assistant_(TV_series)&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=The_Assistant_(TV_series)&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/The_Assistant_(TV_series)","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=The_Assistant_(television)&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","//upload.wikimedia